age_group <- group_by(pf, age, gender) pf.fc_by_age_gender <- summarise(age_group, mean_friend_count = mean(friend_count), median_friend_count = median(friend_count), n = n())

#However I will use that pipeline method: chian function together

fb_fc_by_age_gender=fb%>%
  filter(!is.na(gender))%>%
  group_by(age, gender) %>% 
  summarise(mean_friend_count=mean(friend_count),
            median_friend_count=median(friend_count),
            n=n()) %>%
  arrange(age)

Ratio Plot

Notes:

Plot the ratio of the female to male median_friend_counts using the data frame fb_fc_by_age_gender_wide. Think about what geom you should use. Add a horizontal line to the plot with a y intercept of 1, which will be the base line. Look up the documentation for geom_hline to do that. Use the parameter linetype in geom_hline to make the line dashed.

The linetype parameter can take the values 0-6:

0 = blank, 1 = solid, 2 = dashed 3 = dotted, 4 = dotdash, 5 = longdash 6 = twodash

ENTER YOUR CODE BELOW THIS LINE

geom_hline:There are two ways to use it. You can either specify the intercept of the line in the call to the geom, in which case the line will be in the same position in every panel. Alternatively, you can supply a different intercept for each panel using a data.frame. See the examples for the differences

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = (female/male)), data = fb_fc_by_age_gender_wide)+
  geom_line() +
  geom_hline(linetype = 2,alpha=0.5, yintercept = 1)

we can easily see that for young users th median female users have over two and a half time as many friends as the median male users. clearly it was helpful to condition on age and understanding the relationship of gender with friend_count. this helped assures us that the this patern is robust for users of many differnet ages. and it also highlighted where this differences is most striking. Now there are many processes that can produce this difference, including the baised distribution from which psuedo facebook data was generated. one idea which shows the complexity of interpretation here is that peole from particular countries who more recently joined facebook are more likely to be male with lower friends_counts

Create a variable called year_joined in the pf data frame using the variable tenure and 2014 as the reference year. The variable year joined should contain the year that a user joined facebook.

fb$year_joined= floor(2014 - (fb$tenure/365))

View(fb)

Cut a Variable

Notes: What situation is cut useful in?

In many data analysis settings, it might be useful to break up a continuous variable such as age into a categorical variable. Or, you might want to classify a categorical variable like year into a larger bin, such as 1990-2000. There are many reasons not to do this when performing regression analysis, but for simple displays of demographic data in tables, it could make sense. The cut function in R makes this task simple! The cut function is useful for turning continuous variables into factors.

print(summary(fb$year_joined))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    2005    2012    2012    2012    2013    2014       2
print(table(fb$year_joined))
## 
##  2005  2006  2007  2008  2009  2010  2011  2012  2013  2014 
##     9    15   581  1507  4557  5448  9860 33366 43588    70

Create a new variable in the data frame called year_joined.bucket by using the cut function on the variable year_joined. You need to create the following buckets for the new variable, year_joined.bucket

  (2004, 2009]
  (2009, 2011]
  (2011, 2012]
  (2012, 2014]

Note that a parenthesis means exclude the year and a bracket means include the year.

fb$year_joined.bucket <- cut(fb$year_joined, breaks = c(2004, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014))

Bias-Variance Tradeoff Revisited

Notes:there is a lot of noise in our graph, since we are plotting the mean of y for every possible tenure x value. recall from lesson 4 that we can adjust this noise by bending our x-axis differently. let me show you one of those changes in our bin width.instead of using tenure here i am gonna replace this with differnt version or formula so that i can bend some of tenures together, lets see the difference when we plot this.

p1= ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = 'summary',
            fun = mean)

p2= ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun = mean)

p3= ggplot(aes(x = 30 * round(tenure / 30), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun = mean)

p4= ggplot(aes(x = 90 * round(tenure / 90), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun= mean)

library(gridExtra)
## 
## Attaching package: 'gridExtra'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     combine
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,p4, ncol=1)

notice how slightly less noise we get in plot whenever i multiply it with bigger number. we see with the number 90 very high bias but much less variance. Notice as the bin size increases we see less noise on the plot. our estimates are adjusted since we have more data points for our new values of tenure. in lesson four we introduced as a smoother as one tool for an analyst to use in these type of situation. so instead of using geom_line() here, I would like to use geom_smooth to add a smoother to this.

NOTE: The code changing the binning is substituting x = tenure in the plotting expressions with x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), etc., binning values by the denominator in the round function and then transforming back to the natural scale with the constant in front.

Learn about Bias_variance Trade-off

#instruction Instead of geom_line(), use geom_smooth() to add a smoother to the plot. You can use the defaults for geom_smooth() but do color the line by year_joined.bucket Remember: we are using just geom_smooth, R will just use a perfect statistical method based on our data.

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = year_joined.bucket))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

Histograms Revisited

Notes:

ggplot(aes(price), data=yogurt)+geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

we immediately notice some important discreteness to this distribution, there are appear to be prices which there are many observations, but then no observation in adjacent prices. this makes sense if prices are set in a way that applies to many of the consumers. there are some purchases that involve much lower prices and if we are interested in price sensitivity, we definitely want to consider what sort of variation is in these prices. i want u to notice if you chose a different binwidth we might obscure these discreteness.

so, now we know some about the price. lets figure out on a given purchase occasion how many eight ounce yogurt does a household purchased. to answer this we need to combine accounts of the different yogurts flavors into one variable. we need to use a new function a transform function

###Instruction Create a new variable called all.purchases, which gives the total counts of yogurt for each observation or household. One way to do this is using the transform function. You can look up the function transform and run the examples of code at the bottom of the documentation to figure out what it does. The transform function produces a data frame so if you use it then save the result to ‘yo’!

yogurt= transform(yogurt, all.purchases= strawberry+blueberry+
                    pina.colada+plain+mixed.berry  )

#alternate way
yogurt$all.purchases=yogurt$strawberry + yogurt$blueberry +
  yogurt$pina.colada + yogurt$plain + yogurt$mixed.berry

Sampling Observations

Notes:when familarizing ourselves with a dataset that contians mltiple observations of the same units, it often useful to work with a sample of those unit so that its easy to display the raw data for that sample. in our case of yogurt dataset we might want to look at a small set of household in more detail so that we know what kind of within and between household variation we are working with. this analysis of a sub-sample might come before trying to use within houshold variation as part of model. for example this data set was originally used to model consumer preferences for variety. but before doing that we would want to look at how often we observe household buying yogurt, how often they buy multiple items,and what prices they are buying yogurt at. one way to do this is to look at some sub-sample in more detail.lets pick 16 household ar random and take a closer look.

id%in%sample.ids: just tells to loop over the ids that are in sample.ids variable.so that we go through and create a panel plot for each id of our household.

laarn difference between a%in%b and a==b

face_wrap make the panel for Ids…(we have already identified which ids in %in% methods)

ggplot(aes(x=time, y= price), data=subset(yogurt, id %in% sample.ids))+
    facet_wrap(~id)+geom_line()+
    geom_point(aes(size= all.purchases), pch=1)

The Limits of Cross Sectional Data

Notes: the general idea here is that if we have observatoin over time we can facet it by the primary unit, case, or individual in the data set. for our yogurt data it eas the households that we were faceting over. this faceted time series plot is something we cant generate with our pseudo facebook data set. since we dont havve data on our sample of users over time. lets get back to the facebook data plot:

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(fb, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = year_joined.bucket))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

the facebook data isnt great for examining the process of friends over time. this data set is just a cross section, its just one snap at a fixed point that tells us the characteristics of individual. not the individual over, say, a year. but if we had a dataset like yogurt one, we would be able to track the friendship_initiated over time and compare that with tenure. this would give us better evidence to explain the difference or the drop in friendship_initiated over time as tenure increases

Many Variables

Notes:much of the analysis we have done so far is based on pre-chosen variables, relationship, or qestion of interest then use EDA to let those chose variables speak and surprise us. more recently when analyzing relationship between two variabele we incorporate more variables into the analysis to improve it. for example: by seeing weather a particular relationship is consistent across values of those other variables. in chosing a third, or four variable to plot we relied on our domain knowledge. but often we might want to visualization or summary to help us identify such auxilary variable. in some analysis we may plan to make use of large number of variables perhaps we planning on predicting one variable with 10, 20 or 100 of others. or maybe we wanna summarise a large set of variables into a samller set of dimensions or perhaps we are looking for interesting reslationship among a large set of variable. in such cases we can help speed up our exploratory analysis for data analysis for producing many plots or comparisons at once. this can be one way to let the dataset as a whole speak in part by drawing our attention to variables we didnt have pre existing interest ***
